data.content:
Here are better MSTest assertions for each case:

```csharp
[TestMethod]
public void GetActiveUsers_ReturnsOnlyActiveUsers()
{
    var service = new UserService();
    var users = service.GetActiveUsers();

    // Instead of Assert.IsTrue(users.Count > 0)
    Assert.AreNotEqual(0, users.Count);

    // Instead of Assert.IsTrue(users.All(u => u.IsActive))
    CollectionAssert.AllItemsAreNotNull(users);
    foreach (var user in users)
        Assert.IsTrue(user.IsActive, $"User {user.Name} is not active");

    // Instead of Assert.IsTrue(users.Count() == 3)
    Assert.AreEqual(3, users.Count);

    // Instead of Assert.IsTrue(admin != null)
    var admin = users.Single(u => u.Role == "Admin");
    Assert.IsNotNull(admin);
}
```

**Key improvements:**

| Instead of | Use | Why |
|---|---|---|
| `Assert.IsTrue(x.Count > 0)` | `Assert.AreNotEqual(0, x.Count)` | Shows actual count on failure |
| `Assert.IsTrue(x.Count == 3)` | `Assert.AreEqual(3, x.Count)` | Shows "Expected 3, got 5" |
| `Assert.IsTrue(obj != null)` | `Assert.IsNotNull(obj)` | Clearer failure message |
| `Assert.IsTrue(condition)` | Add a message parameter | `Assert.IsTrue(cond, "why")` |

Also consider `CollectionAssert.Contains(users, expectedUser)` and `CollectionAssert.AreEquivalent(expected, actual)` for comparing entire collections.

The main benefit: when tests fail, you get **diagnostic messages** (e.g., "Expected: 3, Actual: 5") instead of just "Assert.IsTrue failed."
